entation (when the contained"},{"DocComment":" data type reaches its numerical limit) is allowed to panic, wrap, or"},{"DocComment":" saturate. This behavior is defined by the implementation of the [`Step`]"},{"DocComment":" trait. For primitive integers, this follows the normal rules, and respects"},{"DocComment":" the overflow checks profile (panic in debug, wrap in release). Note also"},{"DocComment":" that overflow happens earlier than you might assume: the overflow happens"},{"DocComment":" in the call to `next` that yields the maximum value, as the range must be"},{"DocComment":" set to a state to yield the next value."},{"DocComment":""},{"DocComment":" [`Step`]: crate::iter::Step"},{"DocComment":""},{"DocComment":" # Examples"},{"DocComment":""},{"DocComment":" The `start..` syntax is a `RangeFrom`:"},{"DocComment":""},{"DocComment":" ```"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!((2..), std::ops::RangeFrom { start: 2 });"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!(2 + 3 + 4, (2..).take(3).sum());"},{"DocComment":" ```"},{"DocComment":""},{"DocComment":" ```"},{"DocComment":" let arr = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4];"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!(arr[ ..  ], [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]);"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!(arr[ .. 3], [0, 1, 2      ]);"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!(arr[ ..=3], [0, 1, 2, 3   ]);"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!(arr[1..  ], [   1, 2, 3, 4]); // This is a `RangeFrom`"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!(arr[1.. 3], [   1, 2      ]);"},{"DocComment":" assert_eq!(arr[1..=3], [   1, 2, 3   ]);"},{"DocComment":" ```"}],"inline":null,"rename":null,"public":true},"is_local":false,"opacity":"Foreign","lang_item":"RangeFrom"},"generics":{"regions":[],"types":[{"index":0,"name":"Idx"}],"const_generics":[],"trait_clauses":[],"regions_outlive":[],"types_outlive":[],"trait_type_constraints":[]},"src":"TopLevel","kind":{"Struct":[{"span":{"data":{"file_id":17,"beg":{"line":200,"col":4},"end":{"line":200,"col":18}},"generated_from_span":null},"attr_info":{"attributes":[{"DocComment":" The lower bound of the range (in